# Localized Image Denoising using Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Models (DDPM) on CIFAR-10

This repository contains the implementation of a generative **Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Model (DDPM)** tailored for strategic image denoising and artifact removal. Evaluated on the **CIFAR-10** dataset, this model is designed to smooth out complex noise distributions in selected image regions while preserving critical structural details, edges, and semantic features.

## 🚀 Overview

Traditional denoising filters often blur sharp edges or fail when handling complex, non-Gaussian noise. This project leverages the iterative reverse process of Diffusion Models to strategically reconstruct clean images from degraded versions. 

### Key Features
* **Selective Denoising:** Optimizes noise smoothing in specific regions without destroying underlying high-frequency details.
* **U-Net Backbone:** Utilizes a modified U-Net architecture with self-attention mechanisms and time-step embeddings to predict and subtract noise iteratively.
* **CIFAR-10 Benchmarked:** Trained and evaluated on $32 \times 32$ color images across 10 diverse classes, proving robustness across varying textures and geometries.

---

## 📐 Methodology

The framework operates on the core principles of Markov chains consisting of two main processes:

1. **Forward Process ($q$):** Gradually adds Gaussian noise to a clean image $x_0$ over $T$ timesteps according to a variance schedule $\beta_1, \beta_2, \dots, \beta_T$.
   
   $$q(x_t | x_{t-1}) = \mathcal{N}(x_t; \sqrt{1 - \beta_t}x_{t-1}, \beta_t\mathbf{I})$$

2. **Reverse Process ($p_\theta$):** A neural network (U-Net) learns to predict the noise injected at any given timestep $t$, allowing the model to iteratively reconstruct the denoised image $x_0$ from a noisy input $x_t$.

   $$p_\theta(x_{t-1} | x_t) = \mathcal{N}(x_{t-1}; \mu_\theta(x_t, t), \Sigma_\theta(x_t, t))$$

